observations.recommendation:
We recommended that management:
The Municipal Engineering
1. Coordinate with the barangay captain of Barangay District 2 to facilitate use of the Day Care Center, ensure that it is used as intended and guarantee its cleanliness and continuous maintenance;
2. Instruct the Municipal Engineer to inspect the DCC in Barangay District 3 and look into the possibility of requesting the contractor of its phase 1 to undertake necessary remedial measures, if warranted;
3. Direct the Inspection Committee to conduct thorough inspections of completed projects prior to final acceptance of the projects, in order to ensure that the projects have no defects arising during the warranty period; and
4. Require the Local Development Council to carefully and judiciously plan the development projects to be charged to the 20% DF to ensure that barangay projects charged thereto are used as intended to optimize LGU resources and for maximum benefits may be attained from the projects funded under the 20% EDF

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive;
a. Direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to ensure that the validity of the Performance Security of the projects run through until the issuance of the Certificate of Final Acceptance in accordance with Sections 39.1, 39.3, and 62.2.1 of Revised IRR of RA 9184;
b. Require the Municipal Engineer to monitor project accomplishments to provide a basis for timely extension of Performance Security up to the actual period of completion; and
c. Require the Municipal Accountant to validate the Performance Security attached to the claims for payment if its validity covers up to final acceptance of the project.

For projects not yet issued a Certificate of Final Inspection, management should require the winning bidder to extend the validity of the Performance Security covering the one-year period from date of completion.

We recommended that Management:
1. Require the legislative branch to prepare an activity plan for the participation of its members to league seminars and activities to maximize resources and establish prioritization of attendance;
2. Encourage participation to seminars/conventions conducted within the province/region when these are conducted within the geographical area to lessen costs;
3. Direct municipal officials to ensure that payment of registration fees in attending seminars, trainings, assemblies and conferences sponsored by their respective leagues are supported with proper government official receipts; and
4. Exercise due prudence in the disbursement of government funds to avoid incurrence of excessive expenditures.

We recommended that the LCE direct the MSWDO to:

conduct proper verification and validation of the targeted beneficiaries identified at the barangay level;


grant ESP/SAP and other similar benefits to duly qualified recipients strictly based on the approved and verified SAP Masterlist and to observe the prohibitions stated in DSWD MC No. 09, Series of 2020;

We also recommended that Management require the persons liable in including the names of unqualified beneficiaries in the payrolls to refund immediately the amounts paid to the latter.  

Subsequently, we recommended that Management redistribute the amount refunded to identified qualified beneficiaries, if warranted.

We recommended the following:

The Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the Inventory Committee to conduct complete physical inventory of infrastructure assets  and some equipment and machineries recorded under the SEF and TF books, and render report thereon as required under Section 124, Chapter 7, Volume I of the NGAS Manual.  The progress of the inventory taking should be monitored by the LCE;

Thereafter, the Committee, the General Services Office and the Municipal Accounting Office reconcile all the inventory reports with the books of accounts;


Require the designated Property Officer to maintain property cards and update them periodically to aid in the conduct of physical count and to solve or minimize the perennial problem of unreconciled Accounting and Property records; and

Likewise, the Committee should be warned that failure to perform their duties as Chairman and Members of the Inventory Committee may be a valid ground for filing of administrative charges for gross neglect of duty.

We recommended that the LCE direct the MSWDO to:
conduct proper verification and validation of the targeted beneficiaries identified at the barangay level;
grant ESP/SAP and other similar benefits to duly qualified recipients strictly based on the approved and verified SAP Masterlist and to observe the prohibitions stated in DSWD MC No. 09, Series of 2020;
We also recommended that Management require the persons liable in including the names of unqualified beneficiaries in the payrolls to refund immediately the amounts paid to the latter.  Subsequently, we recommended that Management redistribute the amount refunded to identified qualified beneficiaries, if warranted.

We recommended the following:
The Local Chief Executive (LCE) reorganize the Inventory Committee and require the same to conduct physical inventory and render report thereon as required under Section 124, Chapter 7, Volume I of the NGAS Manual.  The progress of the inventory taking should be monitored by the LCE;
Thereafter, the Committee, the General Services Office and the Municipal Accounting Office reconcile all the inventory reports with the books of accounts;
Require the designated Property Officer to maintain property cards and update them periodically to aid in the conduct of physical count and to solve or minimize the perennial problem of unreconciled Accounting and Property records; and
Require the previous Chairmen of Inventory Committee to explain their failure to conduct inventory and render report thereon.  Likewise, the Committee should be warned that failure to perform their duties as Chairman and Members of the Inventory Committee may be a valid ground for filing of administrative charges for gross neglect of duty.

